<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/19338997-grant-boshoff"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1442648051i/19338997._UY100_CR17,0,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/19338997-grant-boshoff">Grant Boshoff</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<div class='spoiler'>
This answer contains spoilers…
<span class='spoilerAnswerText'>
<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[
  
    Carey, I'll take the fact that the book got you thinking as a compliment. That's part of the joy in writing. But, to your point, in reality identical <a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">…more</a>
    Carey, I'll take the fact that the book got you thinking as a compliment. That's part of the joy in writing. But, to your point, in reality identical twins share DNA but not fingerprints, so the killing of a twin would be considered murder as it is a separate human being. However, the premise in The Copy is that the cloning procedure produced an identical second body (DNA &amp; fingerprints) and is therefore indistinguishable - legally speaking - one from the other. What our current legal system would do with such an occurrence is something that intrigued me too...hence my writing of the story :)<a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">(less)</a>
  
 <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>
</span>
</div>
</span>
</div>
</div>
